    <node id="1. Food as a necessity and morale booster: The traditions of sailor's food and drink highlight the importance of food in historical endeavors such as exploring the seas. Sailors relied on limited supplies for sustenance during long voyages, making food a crucial factor in their health, survival, and overall morale. This concept is still relevant today, as demonstrated by the name &quot;Slimeheads&quot; given to Marsmen. The name emphasizes the centrality of algae-based food (Chlorella and Scenedesmus) for sustenance in space, just as liquid hash and citrus were essential for early seafarers.&#10;   &#10;2. Identity and representation: Just like how &quot;Lobscousers&quot; and &quot;Limey&quot; reflected the dietary habits of early sailors, the name &quot;Slimeheads&quot; represents the unique challenge of feeding large groups of people on spaceships using algae as a primary food source. The term signifies the adaptability and resilience required to survive in harsh environments, emphasizing the significance of understanding historical dietary practices in shaping human identities and histories.&#10;&#10;3. Overcoming challenges through innovation: Seafarers had to innovate and adapt their diets due to limited supplies and the need for preservation, leading to unique food traditions like liquid hash and citrus-infused gin-and-tonic. Similarly, Marsmen have embraced algae as a primary food source, pushing the boundaries of what is considered edible and developing new methods of producing and consuming food in space.&#10;&#10;In summary, the traditions of sailor's food and drink tell us about the importance of food in historical endeavors like exploring the seas by highlighting its role in meeting basic needs, shaping identities, and providing morale boosts during challenging voyages. The name &quot;Slimeheads&quot; for Marsmen and the significance of algae in settling space demonstrate that these lessons remain relevant today, as humans continue to push the boundaries of exploration and adaptation in new environments." />
    <node id=" alien yeast had got into&#10; the stomach of every man aboard, where it fermented each subsequent&#10; bite he ate to a superior grade of sake . And for a third footnote to&#10; the ancient observation, &quot;God sends food, and the Devil sends cooks,&quot;&#10; Marsmen will recall what happened aboard my ship the Charles Partlow&#10; Sale .&#10; &#10; The Sale blasted off from Brady Station in the middle of August, due&#10; in at Piano West in early May. In no special hurry, we were taking&#10; the low-energy route to Mars, a pathway about as long in time as the&#10; human period of gestation. Our cargo consisted mostly of Tien-Shen fir&#10; seedlings and some tons of an arctic grass-seed—these to be planted&#10; in the maria to squeeze out the native blue bugberry vines. We had&#10; aboard the Registry minimum of six men and three officers. Ship's&#10; Surgeon was myself, Paul Vilanova. Our Captain was Willy Winkelmann,&#10; the hardest man in space and very likely the fattest. Ship's Cook was&#10; Robert Bailey.&#10; &#10; Cooking aboard a spacer is a job combining the more frustrating&#10; tensions of biochemistry, applied mycology, high-speed" />
    <node id="The Ship's Cook plays a crucial role in the morale and well-being of the crew on a spacer, as demonstrated by historical examples such as the H.M.S. Ajax fiasco and the Benjo Maru incident. By transforming offal into edible meals, the Ship's Cook performs a daily miracle that can significantly impact the mental state of the crew. Good cooking can boost morale, while poor cooking can lead to discontent, mutiny, or even poisoning.&#10;&#10;In the case of the H.M.S. Ajax fiasco, a galleyman's negligence in handling heavy water from the ship's shielding contaminated Chlorella tanks, leading to deuterium poisoning among the crew members. This incident highlights the importance of proper food preparation and storage on a spacer.&#10;&#10;The Benjo Maru incident involved a Ship's Cook allowing algae-based staff-of-life to become contaminated with a fast-growing Saccharomycodes yeast, causing every man aboard to consume an alcoholic substance that fermented each bite they ate into sake. This example shows how a minor mistake in food preparation can have severe consequences for the entire crew.&#10;&#10;Therefore, the Ship's Cook wields significant power over the well-being and morale of the crew on a spacer, making their role indispensable to the success of any mission." />
    <node id=" Robert Bailey.&#10; &#10; Cooking aboard a spacer is a job combining the more frustrating&#10; tensions of biochemistry, applied mycology, high-speed farming,&#10; dietetics and sewage engineering. It's the Cook's responsibility to&#10; see that each man aboard gets each day no less than five pounds of&#10; water, two pounds of oxygen, and one-and-a-half pounds of dry food.&#10; This isn't just a paragraph from the Spacer Union Contract. It's a&#10; statement of the least fuel a man can run on.&#10; &#10; Twelve tons of water, oxygen, and food would have filled the cargo&#10; compartments to bursting, and left a small ship like the C. P. Sale no reason to reach for Mars. By allowing a colony of Chlorella algae to&#10; work over our used air, water and other effluvia, though, three tons&#10; of metabolites would see us through from Brady Station to Piano West&#10; and back. Recycling was the answer. The molecule of carbohydrate, fat,&#10; protein or mineral that didn't feed the crew fed the algae. And the&#10; algae fed us.&#10; &#10; All waste was used to fertilize our liquid fields. Even the stubble&#10; from our" />
    <node id="Captain Winkelmann was not impressed with the cook's attempt at making a meat substitute and dessert for the crew. He criticized the cook's use of synthetic onions and cycler-salt, and ultimately referred to the food as &quot;this Schweinerei&quot; which means &quot;filth&quot; in his home country's language. The captain refused to eat it, stating that &quot;Mensch ist was er isst&quot; which means &quot;you are what you eat&quot;, implying that he did not want to become the &quot;filth&quot; the cook was feeding him. He also expressed his displeasure with the food by leaving the table and climbing up the ladder from the dining-cubby after making the comment." />
    <node id=" heads like crisp, three-dimensional jigsaw puzzles. The pièce de&#10; résistance was again a &quot;hamburger steak;&quot; but this time the algaeal&#10; mass that made it up was buried in a rich, meaty gravy that was only&#10; faintly green. The essence-of-steak used in these Chlorella cutlets had&#10; been sprinkled with a lavish hand. Garlic was richly in evidence. &quot;It's&#10; so tender,&quot; the radioman joked, &quot;that I can hardly believe it's really&#10; steak.&quot;&#10; &#10; Bailey stared across the dining-cubby toward Winkelmann, silently&#10; imploring the Captain's ratification of his masterpiece. The big&#10; man's pink cheeks bulged and jumped with his chewing. He swallowed.&#10;&quot;Belly-Robber,&quot; Winkelmann said, &quot;I had almost rather you served me&#10; this pond-scum raw than have it all mucked-up with synthetic onions and&#10; cycler-salt.&quot;&#10; &#10; &#10;&#10; &#10; &quot;You seem able enough to choke down Bailey's chow, Captain,&quot; I said. I&#10; gazed at Winkelmann's form, bulbous from a lifetime of surfeit feeding.&#10; &#10;" />
