    <edge source="Captain Willy Winkelmann played a significant role in creating a challenging work environment for Robert Bailey during their space voyage. The Captain's primary concern was to have a reliable and tasty food source for his crew throughout the journey to Mars, which led him to set high expectations for Bailey as the Ship's Cook.&#10;&#10;Winkelmann treated Bailey harshly, criticizing his culinary creations and constantly challenging him to improve. He ordered Bailey to experiment with Chlorella tanks as a food source, expecting him to find ways to produce good food despite the unappetizing ingredients. This pressure from the Captain caused Bailey considerable stress, even though he was an excellent cook and had met or exceeded the expectations of other officers and crew members.&#10;&#10;The story also mentions that Winkelmann often called Bailey to question his culinary skills personally, which added to the challenging work environment. Additionally, the Captain discussed haut cuisine and noble wines with others while they ate algaeburgers and utility water, further highlighting Bailey's struggle to meet his expectations.&#10;&#10;Winkelmann's constant criticism, along with his unrealistic demands for delicious meals from Chlorella-based ingredients, created a stressful work environment for Bailey on their space voyage." target=" enough to accommodate a wart as annoying as&#10; Willy Winkelmann. Cheek-by-jowl every day in a nacelle the size of a&#10; Pullman car, our Captain quickly established himself as a major social&#10; hemorrhoid.&#10; &#10; The Captain's particular patsy was, of course, young Bailey the Cook.&#10; It was Winkelmann who saw humorous possibilities in the entry, &quot;Bailey,&#10; Robert,&quot; on Ship's Articles. He at once renamed our unfortunate&#10; shipmate &quot;Belly-Robber.&quot; It was Winkelmann who discussed haut&#10; cuisine and the properties of the nobler wines while we munched our&#10; algaeburgers and sipped coffee that tasted of utility water. And it was&#10; Captain Willy Winkelmann who never referred to the ship's head by any&#10; other name than The Kitchen Cabinet.&#10; &#10; Bailey tried to feed us by groundside standards. He hid the taste&#10; of synthetic methionine—an essential amino acid not synthesized by&#10; Chlorella—by seasoning our algaeal repasts with pinches of oregano&#10; and thyme. He tinted the pale-green dollops of pressed Chlorella pink,&#10; text">
